Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text, using the `GumboParser` and `HtmlRenderer` libraries from Google's cpp-html library:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>
#include <cstdint>
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
#include <utility>
#include <string_view>
#include "gumbo.h"
#include "html_renderer.h"

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string &markdown) {
    // Parse the markdown string into a Gumbo node tree
    std::unique_ptr<GumboOutput> gumboOutput = GumboParser::parse(&markdown[0], markdown.size());
    if (!gumboOutput) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to parse markdown\n";
        return "";
    }

    // Render the Gumbo node tree into an HTML string
    std::unique_ptr<HtmlRenderer> htmlRenderer = std::make_unique<HtmlRenderer>(gumboOutput->document);
    std::string html;
    htmlRenderer->render(html);

    return html;
}
```
This function uses the `GumboParser` and `HtmlRenderer` classes from the `cpp-html` library to parse the markdown string into a Gumbo node tree, and then render the node tree into an HTML string. The `markdownToHtml` function can be used like this:
```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This example will output the following HTML string:
```html
